node.text:
So excited to be partnering with @sheltertosoldier to help in "Saving Lives, Two at a Time." With the help of my friends and followers, I'm going to be sponsoring a shelter dog to be trained and paired with a military veteran in need of support.  Please consider joining our cause via the link in my bio.  After we raise enough funds to sponsor a shelter dog, I'll be counting on my followers to help us name the dog too!  I'll be sharing lots of updates along this journey and about Shelter to Soldier's work supporting our vets. 

Also check out sheltertosoldier.org for info about their Virtual Gala this Saturday.  They're even auctioning off a private training session with me, so come support our vets and shelter animals!  And thanks to @august_michaelle for the awesome kick-off video! #catsforshelterdogs #sheltertosoldier #savingtwolivesatatime #military #supportourtroops #supportourvets #mentalhealth #fightlife

node.title: Saving two lives at a time...

#shells

node.text:
When I started wrestling in middle school, I joined the boys’ team because that was the only team possible. 

Through my journey, I’ve been inspired by so many other girls and young women who are also pushing to be the first at something or just overcoming obstacles in the fight to excel at their dreams.

PARITY is about all of us, regardless of gender, having a fair chance to pursue our goals and having the proper support systems to do so. 

I joined the @paritynow community to help further that mission.  The company sees the value in female athletes like myself and gets us paid for it. 

The fight for gender pay parity isn’t new, but this IS a new approach in sports and I want to encourage my fellow female athletes to check out paritynow.co to learn more :)

#womeninsport
#parity
#paritynow
#paywomen
#genderpaygap
#ad

node.text:
Update: been a long road.
The first white bikini is me, post baby, pre implants. I could get my entire fit body back after having a baby other than my breasts. I affectionately called them my flap jacks but I was actually a bit bashful at 24 y/o to see myself that way... and my hubby at the time was pretty encouraging to get new knockers.
Now that I look back, I immediately felt increasingly like something was wrong. My hormones were all over the place, my anxiety was odd, I increasingly gained weight (fighting at 125 to 145) and felt more sore and tired with no reasoning. My insomnia was nuts & when I did sleep I sweat pounds worth over night.
My hips and back were constantly in agony, I’d go in to yawning fits every time I needed to workout or get my heart rate going because I was having respiratory issues due to the inflammation. My hair was thinning, I had new food allergy about every 3 months, my eyes were always stoner red & my vision was declining. Memory & concentration were an issue that I always just blamed on being in fist fights (a bit of all of the above which I also treated) as well as the randomly onset depression & fatigue.
My blood tests said I had low estrogen, low testosterone, low dhea and hyperthyroidism. None of which I could treat due to USADA rules, which I understood. 
A few years ago, after an endless search for “what’s wrong with me” I stumbled on an article of a woman who was an athlete & had all the same complaints. After seeing this I researched many women (and men) to recognize I was experiencing Implant Illness and that I needed them out. A struggle I had to face was the decision of “do I do this now” and risk the trouble of not being able to stay active while going through a healing/detox, or get them taken out later, where I limit the amount of time that I get to actually fight/live feeling healthy if it does work & end up a cure. So I chose NOW. I got them out ASAP (most places are on a 6mo-1 yr wait) & I’m so glad I did. I got a new lease on my body & after a while ALL of the symptoms are gone other than some food allergies.
I’m telling you because I got told & I have no regrets... the last vid is me again, 10 years later ♥️
